  "issue_title": "[Bug]: LaTeX rendering is still broken",
  "issue_body": "### Self Checks\n\n- [x] I have searched for existing issues [search for existing issues](https://github.com/infiniflow/ragflow/issues), including closed ones.\n- [x] I confirm that I am using English to submit this report ([Language Policy](https://github.com/infiniflow/ragflow/issues/5910)).\n- [x] Non-english title submitions will be closed directly ( \u975e\u82f1\u6587\u6807\u9898\u7684\u63d0\u4ea4\u5c06\u4f1a\u88ab\u76f4\u63a5\u5173\u95ed ) ([Language Policy](https://github.com/infiniflow/ragflow/issues/5910)).\n- [x] Please do not modify this template :) and fill in all the required fields.\n\n### RAGFlow workspace code commit ID\n\n0.24.0\n\n### RAGFlow image version\n\n0.24.0\n\n### Other environment information\n\n```Markdown\n\n```\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nWhen the output from the LLM contains LaTeX math, ragflow will fail to render the math properly. In previous versions, it will look like [#8954](https://github.com/infiniflow/ragflow/issues/8954). In this new 0.24.0 version, it will cut the response in the middle of the math:\n\n<img width=\"660\" height=\"896\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/b185479c-5b39-4212-95fd-8b9d787a4f03\" />\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nFrom the log, copy the actual LLM response content.\n\nIn a Jupyter Notebook, this piece of code will render the most of it correctly.\n\n```python\ntext = r\"\"\"ACTUAL CONTENT GOES HERE\"\"\"\n\nfrom IPython.display import display, Markdown, Latex\ndisplay(Markdown(text.encode().decode('unicode_escape')))\n```\n\nwhere `text` is the variable containing the response.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```Markdown\n1. Parse the paper given below\n2. Import the agent given below \n3. Ask \"In this paper, the author used some really old parsers, while I am going to use modern T5 models. Hence, it's formula for calculating Model-based Confidence will not work. What could I do to calculate Model-based Confidence for my work?\"\n```\n\n### Additional information\n\nThis is the log contains the LLM response\n\n`agent_response` contains the actual response content.\n\n<details>\n\n```\nragflow-cpu-1  | 2026-02-11 18:11:06,423 INFO     25 handle_task done for task {\"id\": \"1152ec5207b811f1ac583f92f7ca4b97\", \"create_time\": 1770862257125, \"create_date\": \"2026-02-11 18:10:57\", \"update_time\": 1770862257125, \"update_date\": \"2026-02-11 18:10:57\", \"doc_id\": \"e89bb65ae43d11f0a1b4f276361bc6b7\", \"from_page\": 0, \"to_page\": 100000000, \"task_type\": \"memory\", \"priority\": 0, \"begin_at\": null, \"process_duration\": 0.0, \"progress\": 0.0, \"progress_msg\": \"\", \"retry_count\": 0, \"digest\": \"60\", \"chunk_ids\": \"\", \"memory_id\": \"e89bb65ae43d11f0a1b4f276361bc6b7\", \"source_id\": 60, \"message_dict\": {\"user_id\": \"38e8abd861b111f0bd2f0a17e63f93cd\", \"agent_id\": \"81688c5083f011f0bf4992dd7cc36ab6\", \"session_id\": \"81688c5083f011f0bf4992dd7cc36ab6\", \"user_input\": \"Can you repeat the recommended approaches? Your answer is not complete\", \"agent_response\": \"# Recommended Approaches for T5-based Model Confidence (Complete Version)\\n\\nBased on the literature and adapting from Nishida and Matsumoto's framework, here are the complete recommended approaches for calculating model-based confidence with T5 models:\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1. Sequence-Level Log-Probability (Primary Recommendation)\\n\\nFor T5 models, the most direct analog to model-based confidence is the **generation probability**:\\n\\n$$\\nC_{seq}(y|x) = \\\\frac{1}{|y|} \\\\sum_{t=1}^{|y|} \\\\log P(y_t | y_{<t}, x)\\n$$\\n\\nWhere:\\n- *x* = input document/EDUs\\n- *y* = predicted output (dependency structure)\\n- *|y|* = sequence length (for length normalization)\\n- *P(y_t | y_{<t}, x)* = softmax probability of token y_t\\n\\n**Implementation**: In HuggingFace, use `model.generate()` with `return_dict_in_generate=True` and `output_scores=True` to obtain `sequences_scores` (log-probability).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2. Normalized Perplexity-based Confidence\\n\\nConvert log-probability to a perplexity-based confidence score:\\n\\n$$\\nPPL(y|x) = \\\\exp\\\\left(-\\\\frac{1}{|y|} \\\\sum_{t=1}^{|y|} \\\\log P(y_t | y_{<t}, x)\\\\right)\\n$$\\n\\n$$\\nC_{ppl}(y|x) = \\\\frac{1}{PPL(y|x)}\\n$$\\n\\n**Lower perplexity \\u2192 Higher confidence**. Invert and normalize to get a confidence score in [0,1]:\\n\\n$$\\nC_{norm} = \\\\frac{C_{ppl} - C_{min}}{C_{max} - C_{min}}\\n$$\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 3. Document-Level Confidence Aggregation\\n\\nFollowing Nishida and Matsumoto's approach of document-level confidence, aggregate EDU-pair predictions:\\n\\n$$\\nC_{doc}(D) = \\\\frac{1}{|E|} \\\\sum_{(h,d) \\\\in E} C(h, d)\\n$$\\n\\nWhere:\\n- *E* = set of predicted EDU attachments in document *D*\\n- *C(h,d)* = confidence for individual head-dependent pair\\n\\n**Important caveat**: Documents with higher confidence scores are biased to shorter documents [ID:244]. Consider normalizing by document length:\\n\\n$$\\nC_{doc}^{norm}(D) = \\\\frac{C_{doc}(D)}{\\\\alpha \\\\cdot \\\\log(|EDU|) + \\\\beta}\\n$$\\n\\nWhere \\u03b1 and \\u03b2 are tunable hyperparameters.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 4. Entropy-based Uncertainty\\n\\nMeasure prediction uncertainty using output distribution entropy:\\n\\n$$\\nH(y_t) = -\\\\sum_{v \\\\in V} P(v | y_{<t}, x) \\\\log P(v | y_{<t}, x)\\n$$\\n\\n$$\\nC_{entropy}(y|x) = 1 - \\\\frac{1}{|y|} \\\\sum_{t=1}^{|y|} \\\\frac{H(y_t)}{\\\\log|V|}\\n$$\\n\\nWhere:\\n- *V* = vocabulary\\n- *H(y_t)* = entropy at decoding step *t*\\n- Normalized by *log|V|* to scale between [0,1]\\n\\n**High entropy = Low confidence** (model is uncertain).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 5. Token-Level Max Probability\\n\\nFor each generated token, take the maximum softmax probability:\\n\\n$$\\nC_{max}(y|x) = \\\\frac{1}{|y|} \\\\sum_{t=1}^{|y|} \\\\max_{v \\\\in V} P(v | y_{<t}, x)\\n$$\\n\\nThis measures how confident the model is at each decoding step.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 6. Margin-based Confidence\\n\\nMeasure the gap between the top prediction and the second-best:\\n\\n$$\\nC_{margin}(y|x) = \\\\frac{1}{|y|} \\\\sum_{t=1}^{|y|} \\\\left( P(y_t | y_{<t}, x) - P(y_t^{(2)} | y_{<t}, x) \\\\right)\\n$$\\n\\nWhere *y_t^{(2)}* is the second most probable token at step *t*.\\n\\n**Larger margin = Higher confidence**.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 7. Consistency-based Confidence (Multi-sample)\\n\\nUse multiple decoding strategies and measure agreement:\\n\\n**Method A: Multiple Sampling**\\n- Generate *k* samples using different random seeds or temperature settings\\n- Calculate agreement rate:\\n\\n$$\\nC_{consist}(x) = \\\\frac{1}{\\\\binom{k}{2}} \\\\sum_{i < j} \\\\mathbb{1}[y_i = y_j]\\n$$\\n\\n**Method B: Beam vs. Sampling Comparison**\\n- Compare beam search output with nucleus/top-k sampling outputs\\n- Higher agreement = Higher confidence\\n\\n**Method C: MC Dropout**\\n- Apply dropout at inference time multiple times\\n- Measure variance across predictions:\\n\\n$$\\nC_{MC}(x) = 1 - \\\\text{Var}(\\\\{y_1, y_2, ..., y_k\\\\})\\n$$\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary Table\\n\\n| **Approach** | **Formula Basis** | **Pros** | **Cons** |\\n|--------------|-------------------|----------|----------|\\n| Seq-level log-prob | $\\\\frac{1}{|y|}\\\\sum \\\\log P(y_t)$ | Direct, easy to compute | May be overconfident |\\n| Perplexity-based | $1/PPL$ | Intuitive interpretation | Requires normalization |\\n| Document-level aggregation | $\\\\frac{1}{|E|}\\\\sum C(h,d)$ | Matches Nishida's framework | Biased to short docs |\\n| Entropy-based | $1 - \\\\bar{H}/\\\\log|V|$ | Captures uncertainty | Computationally heavier |\\n| Consistency-based | Multi-sample agreement | Robust to noise | Requires multiple passes |\\n| Token-level max prob | $\\\\frac{1}{|y|}\\\\sum \\\\max P$ | Simple | Ignores distribution shape |\\n| Margin-based | Top-1 minus Top-2 prob | Captures decision boundary | May miss multimodal cases |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Recommended Combination\\n\\nFor best results, consider combining multiple approaches:\\n\\n$$\\nC_{final} = \\\\alpha \\\\cdot C_{seq} + \\\\beta \\\\cdot C_{entropy} + \\\\gamma \\\\cdot C_{consist}\\n$$\\n\\nWith weights tuned on a validation set. Additionally:\\n- Apply **length normalization** to avoid bias toward short documents [ID:244]\\n- Use **label class balancing** when selecting pseudo-labeled samples [ID:329]\\n- Consider **human-in-the-loop** for low-confidence examples [ID:329]\"}}\n```\n\n\n\n</details>\n\nUpon further observation, the rendering will stop when '<' happens in the math.\n\n\n\nThe paper for reproducing the issue:\n\n[Nishida and Matsumoto - 2022 - Out-of-Domain Discourse Dependency Parsing via Bootstrapping An Empirical Analysis on Its Effective.pdf](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/25274025/Nishida.and.Matsumoto.-.2022.-.Out-of-Domain.Discourse.Dependency.Parsing.via.Bootstrapping.An.Empirical.Analysis.on.Its.Effective.pdf)\n\n\nThe agent I use:\n\n[Discorse Dialogue Research.json](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/25274075/Discorse.Dialogue.Research.json)",
